  <front>
    <title
      abbrev="ecsv"
    >File Format and MIME type for Enhanced Comma-Separated Values (ECSV) Files.</title>
    <author
      initials="P.D."
      surname="Austin"
      fullname="Paul Austin"
    >
      <organization>Revolution Systems Inc.</organization>
      <address>
        <email>paul.austin@revolsys.com</email>
        <uri>http://www.revolsys.com/</uri>
      </address>
    </author>
    <date
      month="April"
      year="2010" />
    <area>Applications</area>
    <keyword>I-D</keyword>
    <keyword>Internet-Draft</keyword>
    <keyword>CSV</keyword>
    <keyword>Comma-Separated Values</keyword>
    <abstract>
      <t>This document proposes an Enhanced Comma-Separated Values (ECSV) text
        file format and registers the associated file extension "ecsv" and MIME
        type "text/ecsv".</t>
    </abstract>
  </front>
  <middle>
    <section
      anchor="intro"
      title="Introduction"
    >
    </section>
    <section
      anchor="notation"
      title="Notational conventions"
    >
      <t>
        The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT",
        "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this
        document are to be interpreted as described in
        <xref
          target="RFC2119"
        >RFC 2119</xref>
        .
      </t>
      <t>UCS characters are designated by the U+HHHH notation, where HHHH is a
        string of from 4 to 6 hexadecimal digits representing the character
        number in ISO/IEC 10646.</t>
    </section>
    <section
      anchor="mime"
      title="MIME Type Registration of text/ecsv"
    >
      <t>
        This section provides the media-type registration application (as per
        <xref
          target="RFC2048"
        >RFC 2048</xref>
        .
      </t>
      <t>
        <list
          style="hanging"
        >
          <t
            hangText="To:"
          >ietf-types@iana.org</t>
          <t
            hangText="Subject:"
          >Registration of MIME media type text/ecsv</t>
          <t
            hangText="MIME media type name:"
          >text</t>
          <t
            hangText="MIME subtype name:"
          >ecsv</t>
          <t
            hangText="Required parameters:"
          > none</t>
          <t
            hangText="Optional parameters:"
          > none</t>
          <t
            hangText="Encoding considerations:"
          >
            <list
              style="hanging"
            >
              <t
                hangText="Character set:"
              >
                ECSV documents MUST be encoded using the UTF-8 character set as
                defined in
                <xref
                  target="RFC3629"
                >RFC 3629</xref>
                .
              </t>
              <t
                hangText="Line breaks:"
              >
                ECSV documents MUST use CRLF to denote line breaks as per
                section 4.1.1. of
                <xref
                  target="RFC2046"
                >RFC 2046</xref>
                .
              </t>
            </list>
          </t>
          <t
            hangText="Security considerations:"
          >ECSV files contain passive text data that should not pose any risks.
            However, it is possible in theory that malicious binary data may be
            included in order to exploit potential buffer overruns in the
            program processing ECSV data. Additionally, private data may be
            shared via this format (which of course applies to any text data).
          </t>
          <t
            hangText="Interoperability considerations:"
          >
            Unlike plain CSV as defined in
            <xref
              target="RFC4180"
            >RFC 4180</xref>
            the ECSV specification implements formal rules as to the encoding
            and structure of ECSV documents. To ensure interoperability
            applications creating ECSV documents MUST follow the rules defined
            in the ECSV specification. Applications reading ECSV documents MAY
            elect to handle badly formed documents but SHOULD give a warning if
            a document is badly formed.
          </t>
          <t
            hangText="Published specification:"
          >This document "File Format and MIME type for Enhanced Comma-Separated
            Values (ECSV) Files" provides a formal specification for the ECSV
            format.</t>
          <t
            hangText="Applications that use this media type:"
          >Spreadsheet programs, web services, data processing application and
            various data conversion utilities</t>
          <t
            hangText="Additional information:"
          >
            <list
              style="hanging"
            >
              <t
                hangText="Magic number(s):"
              >none</t>
              <t
                hangText="File extension(s):"
              >ecsv</t>
              <t
                hangText="Macintosh File Type
          Code(s):"
              >TEXT</t>
            </list>
          </t>
          <t
            hangText="Person &amp; email address to contact for further information:"
          >Paul Austin &lt;paul.austin@revolsys.com&gt;</t>
          <t
            hangText="Intended usage:"
          >COMMON</t>
          <t
            hangText="Author/Change controller:"
          >IESG</t>
        </list>
      </t>
    </section>
